ity of Labour Governments and the capture of teacher training establishments by left wing dogmatists. &#10;Some time ago I visited a museum in the Scottish highlands that been a one-room school in the 19th century. Some of the work prepared by the children over a century ago was on display. There for all to see were erudite essays, serious mathematics and demonstrations of an excellent knowledge of classical languages. Nor were the pupils a pampered elite: on the contrary, they were children of farm workers and crofters, all no more than twelve years old. &#10;What a dramatic comment on the pitiful standards of state education of our day. And yet the NUT and the educational establishment continue to fight all attempts at reform tooth and nail. How utterly shameful. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1071" language="en" documentId="818" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Huroner" date="07 January 2011 3:35pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/9055023" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="3" thumbsDown="0" origId="818" notes="" title="Why I home school my children"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="221"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="222" end="405"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="406" end="861"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="862" end="1071"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>